## 1. Copy the bundle onto your web server

Serve `widget.js` and `widget.css` as static assets under a path you control.

**bash**

```bash
cp dist/widget.js public/static/widget.js
cp dist/widget.css public/static/widget.css
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item dist/widget.js public/static/widget.js
Copy-Item dist/widget.css public/static/widget.css
```

> Build-time-frozen frontend containers (Docker images, CDN-baked bundles)
> need a **rebuild** before the new assets take effect — copying files
> into a running container is a no-op.

## 2. Add the `<link>` and `<script>` to every page

Near the closing `</body>`:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/widget.css" />
<script
  src="/static/widget.js"
  defer
  data-backend-url="{{atwBackendOrigin}}"
  data-api-base-url="{{hostApiOrigin}}"
  data-auth-mode="{{authMode}}"
{{#if authTokenKey}}  data-auth-token-key="{{authTokenKey}}"
{{/if}}  data-launcher-position="bottom-right"
  data-locale="{{locale}}"
{{#if loginUrl}}  data-login-url="{{loginUrl}}"
{{/if}}></script>
```

The widget reads its tool catalogue at boot from
`{{atwBackendOrigin}}/tools` — there is no `data-allowed-tools`
attribute (FR-015).

Place the tag on the layout/partial that renders site-wide so the widget
appears on every page.

## 3. CORS configuration on your host API

Your host API at `{{hostApiOrigin}}` must accept browser requests from the
storefront origin `{{hostPageOrigin}}`. The widget sends `Authorization`
and `Content-Type` headers; the action manifest currently uses
`GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE`.

Required response headers:

- `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: {{hostPageOrigin}}`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Authorization, Content-Type`
{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}- `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`
{{/if}}

If you are not sure how to add these headers in your stack, the
checklist below covers the common ones. Use whichever applies; **REPLACE
THIS** if your stack is different.

- **Express**: `app.use(require("cors")({ origin: "{{hostPageOrigin}}", methods: ["GET","POST","PUT","PATCH","DELETE","OPTIONS"], allowedHeaders: ["Authorization","Content-Type"]{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}, credentials: true{{/if}} }))`
- **Fastify**: `fastify.register(require("@fastify/cors"), { origin: "{{hostPageOrigin}}", methods: ["GET","POST","PUT","PATCH","DELETE","OPTIONS"], allowedHeaders: ["Authorization","Content-Type"]{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}, credentials: true{{/if}} })`
- **Plain Node `http`**: handle `OPTIONS` explicitly and emit the headers above.

## 4. Run the ATW backend

The backend container reads its config from environment variables. The
emitted `atw/.env.example` contains every value already inlined from
`project.md`; you only need to paste your `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.

**bash**

```bash
cp atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw/.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm \
  --env-file atw/.env \
  -p 4000:4000 \
  atw_backend:latest
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw\.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm `
  --env-file atw/.env `
  -p 4000:4000 `
  atw_backend:latest
```

The backend requires Postgres with the `pgvector` extension. The
`docker-compose.yml` shipped with the demo wires this up; the env
variable `DATABASE_URL` in `atw/.env.example` already points at the
default container address.

## 5. Static assets

For Vite / plain HTML / Next.js, place `widget.js` and `widget.css` in
your `public/` directory (or whatever your stack serves as static files).
Build-time-frozen containers must be rebuilt before changes take effect.

